==English==

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[fōdor]]''

===Pronunciation===
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɒdə(r)|-ɒdə(r)]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# Food for animals.
# A weight by which lead and some other metals were formerly sold, in England, varying from 19 1/2 to 24 [[cwt]].; a [[fother]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1866''', Now measured by the old hundred, that is, 108 lbs. the charrus contains nearly 19 1/2 hundreds, that is it corresponds to the fodder, or fother, of modern times. &mdash; James Edwin Thorold Rogers, ''A History of Agriculture and Prices in England'', Volume 1, p. 168.
# {{cattag|slang|drafting|design}} [[tracing paper|Tracing paper]].

